{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}} {{Infobox organisation | name = BRAC | image = BRAC logo.svg | image_size = | alt = Logo | caption = | predecessor = {{unbulleted list|Building Resources Across Communities | Bangladesh Rehabilitation Assistance Committee|Bangladesh Rural Advancement Committee}} | formation = {{start date|1972|||df=yes}} | founder = [[Fazle Hasan Abed]] | type = Non-profit | purpose = [[International development]] | headquarters = [[Dhaka]], Bangladesh | key_people = [[Fazle Hasan Abed]], Chairperson | revenue = {{increase}}{{BDTConvert|6053.7|c}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.brac.net/images/reports/2016/Bangladesh-Annual-Report-2016.pdf |title=Bangladesh Annual Report |website=BRAC |access-date=14 December 2017}}</ref> | revenue_year = 2016 | expenses = {{increase}}{{BDTConvert|4323.3 |c}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.brac.net/images/reports/2016/Bangladesh-Annual-Report-2016.pdf |title=Bangladesh Annual Report |website=BRAC |access-date=14 December 2017}}</ref> | expenses_year = 2016 | staff = 97,742<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hrd.brac.net/circular/pdf_file/staffposition/December%202016.PDF |title=December 2016 |website=BRAC |access-date=14 December 2017}}</ref> | num_staff_year = 2016 | website = {{URL|brac.net}} }}
'''BRAC''', an [[international development]] organisation based in [[Bangladesh]], is the largest [[Non-governmental organisation|non-governmental development organisation]] in the world, in terms of number of employees as of September 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.dhakatribune.com/op-ed/2016/apr/27/creative-response-challenge-change|title=A creative response to the challenge for change|last=|first=|date=|newspaper=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=7 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/development-policy/interview/ngo-founder-sustainable-development-goals-will-work/|title=NGO founder: Sustainable Development Goals will work|website=EurActiv.com|access-date=7 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |date=18 February 2010 |title=BRAC in business |url=http://www.economist.com/node/15546464 |magazine=The Economist |quote=Called BRAC, it is by most measures the largest, fastest-growing non-governmental organisation (NGO) in the world}}</ref> Established by [[Fazle Hasan Abed|Sir Fazle Hasan Abed]] in 1972 after the [[independence of Bangladesh]], BRAC is present in all 64 [[districts of Bangladesh]] as well as 13 other countries in Asia, Africa, and the Americas.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}
BRAC states that it employs over 100,000 people, roughly 70 percent of whom are women, and that it reaches more than 126 million people with its services.<ref name=":0">{{cite web |url=http://www.brac.net/partnership?view=page |title=BRAC at a Glance |date= |work= |website=brac.net | accessdate=}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=September 2016}}<ref>[https://www.fastcompany.com/1753519/brac-largest-global-anti-poverty-organization-and-its-secret Alice Korngold, 17 May 2011, "BRAC Is The Largest Global Anti-Poverty Organization, And It’s A Secret" at fastcompany.com] Accessed 4 April 2017</ref> The organisation is partly self-funded through a number of social enterprises that include a dairy and food project, a chain of retail handicraft stores called [[Aarong]], seed and Agro{{what?|date=September 2017}}, and chicken. BRAC has operations in 14 countries of the world.<ref name=":0" />{{Primary source inline|date=September 2016}}
==History== [[Image:Fazle Hasan Abed.jpg|thumb|[[Sir Fazle Hasan Abed|Sir Fazlé Hasan Abed]], founder of BRAC]]
Known formerly as the Bangladesh Rehabilitation Assistance Committee, then as the Bangladesh Rural Advancement Committee, and later as Building Resources Across Communities,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.innovations.harvard.edu/sites/default/files/102991.pdf |title=BRAC: Building Resources Across Communities, The Coproduction of Governance: Civil Society, the Government, and the Private Sector |last=Abed |first=Fazle Hasan |website=Government Innovators Network |publisher=Harvard University |accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref> BRAC was initiated in 1972 by [[Fazle Hasan Abed|Sir Fazlé Hasan Abed]] at [[Sullah Upazila|Shallah Upazillah]] in the district of [[Sunamganj]] as a small-scale relief and rehabilitation project to help returning war refugees after the [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] of 1971.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hbs.edu/businesshistory/emerging-markets/pages/profile-detail.aspx?profile=fhabed |title=Interview with Fazle Hasan Abed |website=Creating Emerging Markets |publisher=Harvard Business School}}</ref> 14 thousand homes had to be rebuilt as part of the relief effort, as well as several hundred fishing boats; BRAC claims to have done this within nine months, as well as opening medical centres and providing other essential services.<ref>Annual Report, 1990, BRAC</ref>{{Secondary source needed|date=September 2016}}
Until the mid-1970s, BRAC concentrated on community development through village development programmes that included agriculture, fisheries, [[cooperatives]], rural crafts, [[adult literacy]], health and family planning, vocational training for women and construction of community centres. A Research and Evaluation Division (RED) was set up to evaluate its activities and decide direction, and in 1977, BRAC began taking a more targeted approach by creating Village Organisations (VO) to assist the landless, small farmers, artisans, and vulnerable women. That same year BRAC set up a commercial printing press to help finance its activities. The handicraft retail chain called Aarong, was established the following year.<ref name=Aarong>[http://www.aarong.com/about-aarong/ "This ethical brand began in 1978"... "supports 65,000 artisans with fair terms" in about-aarong at aarong.com] Accessed 6 April 2017</ref>
In 1979, BRAC entered the health field by establishing a nationwide Oral Therapy Extension Programme (OTEP), a campaign to combat [[diarrhoea]], the leading cause of the high child mortality rate in Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Chowdhury |first1=A. M. Raza |last2=Cash |first2=Richard A. |date=1996 |title=A Simple Solution: Teaching Millions to Treat Diarrhoea at Home |publisher=University Press |location=Dhaka, Bangladesh |isbn=9840513419}}</ref>{{page needed|date=November 2015}} [[Education in Bangladesh|Non Formal Primary Education]] was started by BRAC in 1985.<ref>[http://schugurensky.faculty.asu.edu/moments/1985brac.html Daniel Schugurensky: 1985 - BRAC begins non-formal primary education for poor children in Bangladesh, History of Education: Selected Moments of the 20th Century at schugurensky.faculty.asu.edu] Accessed 6 April 2017</ref>
In 1986, BRAC started its Rural Development Programme that incorporated four major activities – institution building including functional education and training, credit operation, income and employment generation and support service programmes.{{Citation needed|date=September 2016}}
In 1991, the Women's Health Development program commenced. The following year BRAC established a Centre for Development Management (CDM) in [[Rajendrapuram|Rajendrapur]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2016}}
Its Social Development, Human Rights and Legal Services programme was launched in 1996.{{Citation needed|date=September 2016}}
In 1998, BRAC's Dairy and Food project was commissioned.{{Citation needed|date=September 2016}} BRAC launched an Information Technology Institute the following year.{{Citation needed|date=September 2016}}
In 2001, BRAC established a university called [[BRAC University]].<ref>[http://admissions.bracu.ac.bd/academia/ "BRAC University was established by BRAC in 2001" at bracu.ac.bd/academia/] Accessed 8 April 2017</ref>
==Programmes== {{NPOV-section|date=September 2017}} {{Quote box| width=25% |align=right |quote=BRAC has done what few others have – they have achieved success on a massive scale, bringing life-saving health programs to millions of the world's poorest people. They remind us that even the most intractable health problems are solvable, and inspire us to match their success throughout the developing world. |source=[[Bill Gates]], Co-chair, [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation]] Global Health Award, 2004 |}}
===Economic development=== Microfinance, introduced in 1974, is BRAC's oldest programme. It spans all districts of Bangladesh.<ref name="microfinance">{{cite web |url=http://www.brac.net/content/microfinance |title=Microfinance |website=BRAC |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110625011027/http://brac.net/content/microfinance |archive-date=25 June 2011 |access-date=21 February 2012}}</ref><ref name="Barber">{{cite journal |last=Barber |first=Ben |date=May 2002 |title=No Free Lunch |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-86396661.html |journal=World & I |volume=17 |issue=5 |via=[[HighBeam Research]] |subscription=yes}}</ref> It provides collateral-free loans to mostly poor, landless, rural women, enabling them to generate income and improve their [[standards of living]].<ref name="microfinance" /><ref name="Barber" /> BRAC's microcredit program has funded over $1.9 billion in loans in its first 40 years.{{Citation needed|date=September 2016}} 95% of BRACs microloan customers are women.<ref name="AR2014" /> According to BRAC, the repayment rate is over 98%.<ref name="Glance2012" />. BRAC started community empowerment programme back in 1988 all over the country.
BRAC founded its retail outlet, Aarong (Bengali for "village fair") in 1978 to market and distribute products made by indigenous peoples. Aarong services about 65,000 artisans, and sells gold and silver jewelry, hand loom, leather crafts, etc.<ref name=Aarong/>
===Education=== BRAC is one of the largest NGOs involved in primary education in [[Bangladesh]].<ref name="Ardt2005" /> As of the end of 2012, it had more than 22,700 non-formal primary schools with a combined enrolment of 670,000 children.<ref name="Glance2012">{{cite web |url=http://www.brac.net/sites/default/files/BRAC-at-a-glance-december-2012.pdf |title=BRAC at a Glance |date=December 2012 |website=BRAC |access-date=12 February 2016}}</ref>{{Secondary source needed|date=September 2016}} Its schools constitute three-quarters of all NGO non-formal primary schools in the country.<ref name="Ardt2005">{{cite web |url=http://rih.stanford.edu/rosenfield/resources/Primary%20Education%20in%20Bangladesh.pdf |title=Report on Primary Education in Bangladesh: Challenges and Successes |last1=Ardt |first1=Kalene |last2=Hastings |first2=Chas |last3=Hopkins |first3=Katie |last4=Knebel |first4=Robin |last5=Loh |first5=Jun |last6=Woods |first6=Rodney |date=2005 |website=Rethinking International Health |publisher= Stanford University School of Medicine |access-date=21 February 2012}}</ref>
BRAC's education programme provides [[Education in Bangladesh#Non-formal primary education|non-formal primary education]] to those left out of the formal education system, especially poor, rural, or disadvantaged children, and drop-outs.<ref name="AR2014">{{cite web |url=http://brac.net/sites/default/files/ar2014/BRAC-annual-report-14.pdf |title=BRAC Bangladesh Annual Report 2014 |website=BRAC |format=PDF |access-date=25 November 2015}}</ref> Its schools are typically one room with one teacher and no more than 33 students. Core subjects include mathematics, social studies and English. The schools also offer extracurricular activities.<ref name="Ardt2005" /> They incentivise schooling by providing food, allowing flexible learning hours, and conferring scholarships contingent on academic performance.<ref name="Dawson">{{cite web |url=http://sanisoft.tripod.com/bdeshedu/gender.html |title=Gender Differences |website=Education in Bangladesh, a Dawson College term paper |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110824202000/http://sanisoft.tripod.com/bdeshedu/gender.html |archive-date=24 August 2011 |access-date=21 February 2012}}</ref>
Bangladesh has reduced the gap between male and female attendance in schools.<ref name="Dawson" /> The improvement in female enrollment, which has largely been at the primary level, is in part attributable to BRAC.<ref name="Ardt2005" /> Roughly 60% of the students in their schools are girls.<ref name="AR2014" />
===Public health=== BRAC started providing public healthcare in 1972 with an initial focus on [[curative care]] through paramedics and a self-financing health insurance scheme. The programme went on to offer integrated health care services.{{Citation needed|date=September 2016}}
[[Image:A community health worker conducting a survey in the Korail slum, Bangladesh (8630810827).jpg|right|thumb|A BRAC community health worker conducting a survey in the Korail slum, Bangladesh]]BRAC's 2007 impact assessment of its North West Microfinance Expansion Project testified to increased awareness of legal issues, including those of marriage and divorce, among women participants in BRAC programs. Furthermore, women participants' self-confidence was boosted and incidence of domestic violence were found to have declined.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ode.ausaid.gov.au/publications/documents/microfinance-issues-note.pdf |title=Microfinance, gender and aid effectiveness |last1=Rogers |first1=Cate |last2=O'Farrell |first2=Sue-Ellen |date=October 2008 |website=AusAID Office of Development Effectiveness |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110517002106/http://www.ode.ausaid.gov.au/publications/documents/microfinance-issues-note.pdf |archive-date=17 May 2011 |access-date=21 February 2012}}</ref> One of the most prominent forms of violence against women, [[acid throwing]], has been decreasing by 15-20% annually since the enactment in 2002 of legislation specifically targeting acid violence.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lawschool.cornell.edu/news-center/upload/Combating-Acid-Violence-Report.pdf |title=Combating Acid Violence in Bangladesh, India, and Cambodia |last=Avon Global Center for Women and Justice at Cornell Law School, and the New York City Bar Association |date=2011 |website=Cornell Law School |format=PDF |access-date=12 February 2016}}</ref>
===Disaster relief=== BRAC conducted one of the largest NGO responses to [[Cyclone Sidr]] which hit vast areas of the south-western coast in Bangladesh in mid-November 2007.{{Citation needed|date=September 2016}} BRAC distributed emergency relief materials, including food and clothing, to over 900,000 survivors, provided medical care to over 60,000 victims and secured safe supplies of drinking water. BRAC is now focusing on long-term rehabilitation, which will include agriculture support, infrastructure reconstruction and livelihood regeneration.<ref name="AR2007">Annual Report, 2007</ref>{{Secondary source needed|date=September 2016}}
==Partnership with the Nike Foundation== BRAC has a collaboration with [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]]'s Girl Effect campaign to launch a new program to reach out to teenagers in [[Uganda]] and [[Tanzania]].<ref>{{cite press release |date=28 May 2008 |title=Nike Foundation and Buffetts join to invest $100 million in girls |url=http://www.nikefoundation.org/files/The_Girl_Effect_News_Release.pdf |publisher=Nike Foundation |format=PDF |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004165309/http://www.nikefoundation.org/files/The_Girl_Effect_News_Release.pdf |archive-date=4 October 2011}}</ref>{{Secondary source needed|date=September 2016}}
==BRAC donors== In 2006 BRAC received donations from Directorate-General for International Cooperation (DGIS) and Government of the Netherlands / Embassy of the Kingdom of the Netherlands (EKN).
In 2011 the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation (BMGF) joined the list of BRAC donors.
In 2012 the Department for International Development (DFID), Government of the UK and Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (DFAT), and Australian Government (SPA) (under the strategic partnership arrangement) became BRAC donors as well. <ref>https://www.brac.net/water-sanitation-hygiene/item/828-donors-and-partners</ref>
==Countries where BRAC operates== * Asia: [[Bangladesh]], [[Afghanistan]], [[Sri Lanka]], [[Pakistan]], [[Philippines]], [[Nepal]], [[Myanmar]] * Africa: [[Uganda]], [[Tanzania]], [[South Sudan]], [[Liberia]], [[Sierra Leone]] * Caribbean: [[Haiti]] * BRAC provides technical assistance to organisations in [[Haiti]], [[Sudan]], and [[Indonesia]] * BRAC has affiliate organisations in the [[United Kingdom]] and [[United States]]
