{{Short description|American painter}} {{Refimprove|date=August 2018}}
'''Charles Kassler Jr''' (September 9, 1897, [[Denver]], Colorado–April 3, 1979, [[San Diego, California]]) was a [[Painting|painter]], [[printmaker]], and [[lithographer]].
==Early life== He lost a hand during a high school [[chemistry]] [[experiment]]. He studied [[art]] and [[architecture]] at [[Princeton University]] and the [[Chicago Art Institute]].
==Career== From 1925 to 1932 Kassler continued his studies while living at various times in [[New Mexico]], [[Europe]], and [[North Africa]]. While in [[France]], he apprenticed himself to a well-known [[fresco]] painter. After moving to [[Los Angeles]] in 1933, he painted the two largest frescoes done under the [[Treasury Section of Fine Arts|WPA]]; ''The [[Bison]] Hunt'' for the [[Los Angeles Public Library|Central Library]] in Downtown Los Angeles which was destroyed by [[weather]] damage and ''Pastoral California'', at Plummer Auditorium in Fullerton, in [[Orange County, California|Orange County]]. It was whitewashed in 1938, just four years after Kassler completed it, but was restored in 1997 after spending almost 60 years hidden from view. Kassler was also commissioned by the WPA to paint eight fresco lunette murals for the [[Beverly Hills, California]] post office funded by the [[Treasury Section of Fine Arts]]. The murals depict the history of the Pony Express, postal service, and the daily life of the common American family. The post office is now home to the Wallis Annenberg Center for the Performing Arts. After creating murals for the WPA, Kassler taught at [[Chouinard Art Institute]] and later worked as a [[designer]] in the [[aerospace]] industry.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Wallis Annenberg Center for the Performing Arts|url=http://www.thewallis.org/building-history|website=www.thewallis.org/building|publisher=The Wallis Organization|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref>
